ization has transformed media systems and policies throughout Latin America. Following an extensive overview by editors Elizabeth Fox and Silvio Waisbord, the contributors investigate the interaction of local politics and global media in individual Latin American countries. Some of the issues they discuss include the privatization and liberalization of the media, the rise of media conglomerates, the impact of trade agreements on media industries, the role of the state, the mediazation of politics, the state of public television, and the role of domestic and global forces. The contributors address these topics with a variety of theoretical approaches, combining institutional, historical, economic, and legal perspectives.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aMass media policyzLatin America. 0aMass mediaxPolitical aspectszLatin America. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aAmaral, Roberto, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAparicio, Fernando Calero, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFaraone, Roque, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFox, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFox, Elizabeth, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFuenzalida, Valerio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGalperín, Hernán, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJanus, Noreene, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMayobre, José Antonio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOrué Pozzo, Aníbal, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPeirano, Luis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRockwell, Rick,